00:03:13.362 --> 00:03:16.380
- Broke my back in two
places, and crushed

00:03:16.380 --> 00:03:19.660
my entire left chest in,
and punctured my lung.

00:03:19.660 --> 00:03:22.050
Had to be medevacked
to Kalispell Medical

00:03:22.050 --> 00:03:29.490
Center in Montana, where they
fused my spine from my thoracic

00:03:29.490 --> 00:03:31.690
9 to lumbar 2.

00:03:31.690 --> 00:03:33.240
The pain got worse and worse.

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:37.640
And I had to take more and more
opiates to control the pain.

00:03:37.640 --> 00:03:40.802
Got so bad that I couldn't
stand it any longer.

00:03:44.204 --> 00:03:51.490
They fused my lumber
2 to my lumbar 3.

00:03:51.490 --> 00:03:58.630
Everything from Norco to
OxyContin, oxycodone, Ultram,

00:03:58.630 --> 00:04:04.630
muscle relaxers, sleeping
aids because I couldn't sleep,

00:04:04.630 --> 00:04:10.410
and the pain wouldn't go away.

00:04:10.410 --> 00:04:14.085
You become socially
isolated by your pain

00:04:14.085 --> 00:04:17.175
because people don't want
to see you suffer like that.

00:04:17.175 --> 00:04:21.910
Pain probably went from
7 to 10 all the time.

00:04:21.910 --> 00:04:24.220
The times it was so bad
I couldn't stand it,

00:04:24.220 --> 00:04:26.710
I would just--

00:04:26.710 --> 00:04:29.230
frankly, I got to a point
where I wanted to die.

00:04:29.230 --> 00:04:29.730
It was--

00:04:29.730 --> 00:04:30.230
- Wow.

00:04:35.065 --> 00:04:39.950
- Well, finally, I went to a
surgeon in Spokane, Washington.

00:04:39.950 --> 00:04:42.764
And they breezed into
the room and said

00:04:42.764 --> 00:04:44.430
they'd look at my
charts and everything.

00:04:44.430 --> 00:04:47.380
And the only thing that
was going to do me any good

00:04:47.380 --> 00:04:51.885
was [LAUGHS] what he called
the Blue Plate Special.

00:04:51.885 --> 00:04:54.320
He said, it's going
to take two surgeries.

00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:58.350
It'll take probably at least a
full day and probably two days.

00:04:58.350 --> 00:05:01.380
And we got to break
your back in two places.

00:05:01.380 --> 00:05:04.380
We're going to clean out all the
stenoses in your spinal canal

00:05:04.380 --> 00:05:10.250
and in your nerve root canals,
and on, and on, and on.

00:05:10.250 --> 00:05:13.190
In the end, he said we're going
to fuse you from your collar

00:05:13.190 --> 00:05:15.750
bone to your hips.

00:05:15.750 --> 00:05:18.275
And I said, but I'm--

00:05:18.275 --> 00:05:20.810
he said, it's not a good option.

00:05:20.810 --> 00:05:23.260
But he said it's the only
one that will work for you.

00:05:23.260 --> 00:05:25.010
Your back's a mess.

00:05:25.010 --> 00:05:26.280
I need another opinion.

00:05:26.280 --> 00:05:31.190
And so I got an
appointment with Dr. David

00:05:31.190 --> 00:05:37.470
Hanscom at Swedish Medical in
Seattle and went to see him.

00:05:37.470 --> 00:05:39.810
He said I see
nothing in your spine

00:05:39.810 --> 00:05:42.210
that would cause
the pain you feel.

00:05:42.210 --> 00:05:45.390
It's like the phantom
wound syndrome.

00:05:45.390 --> 00:05:49.870
Amputees often
feel the same pain

00:05:49.870 --> 00:05:51.685
after a limb that
is giving them pain

00:05:51.685 --> 00:05:55.500
is amputated as they did
before they lost the limb.

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:57.750
And it's, again, the
rewiring of the brain.

00:05:57.750 --> 00:06:00.430
He said, what I'm
pioneering, along

00:06:00.430 --> 00:06:05.730
with some other
physicians, a program that

00:06:05.730 --> 00:06:12.000
will provide an alternative to
having yet more spinal fusions.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:18.120
And he explained that only
around 15% to 30%, at the most,

00:06:18.120 --> 00:06:23.420
of spinal fusions are ever
successful in alleviating pain,

00:06:23.420 --> 00:06:26.640
even over the near term,
let alone the long term.

00:06:26.640 --> 00:06:30.646
And so he said, I would
like you to try my program.

00:06:30.646 --> 00:06:33.690
I said, well, what
does it consist of?

00:06:33.690 --> 00:06:36.230
And he said, well, the
first thing you can do

00:06:36.230 --> 00:06:39.035
is read my book on the subject.

00:06:39.035 --> 00:06:41.340
But he said, immediately,
you can start what

00:06:41.340 --> 00:06:44.820
we call expressive writing.

00:06:44.820 --> 00:06:46.280
And I said, well, what is that?

00:06:46.280 --> 00:06:50.460
And he said, well, you sit
down 15 minutes in the morning

00:06:50.460 --> 00:06:52.470
and 15 minutes at night
and you write down

00:06:52.470 --> 00:06:57.510
every negative thought you have
about anything in long hand,

00:06:57.510 --> 00:06:59.010
and you tear it up.

00:06:59.010 --> 00:07:00.870
And you throw it away.

00:07:00.870 --> 00:07:02.795
And I said, what?

00:07:02.795 --> 00:07:04.952
[LAUGHING]

00:07:04.952 --> 00:07:07.080
First of all, I said, that
sounds like snake oil.

00:07:07.080 --> 00:07:08.440
I was really honest about it.

00:07:08.440 --> 00:07:10.780
I said, I'm a career scientist.

00:07:10.780 --> 00:07:12.960
And I'm taught to be
a critical thinker,

00:07:12.960 --> 00:07:15.540
and by nature, skeptical anyway.

00:07:15.540 --> 00:07:19.000
So I frankly think this
sounds like snake oil.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.780
And he said, wait and think
what you want, he said politely.

00:07:21.780 --> 00:07:24.500
But he said, you can always
be filleted like a salmon.

00:07:24.500 --> 00:07:25.386
[LAUGHING]

00:07:25.386 --> 00:07:27.950
And he said, there'll be plenty
of surgeons who will do that,

00:07:27.950 --> 00:07:29.580
but I won't.

00:07:29.580 --> 00:07:37.260
And he said, or you can try this
technique and the whole program

00:07:37.260 --> 00:07:39.460
eventually.

00:07:39.460 --> 00:07:43.090
I said to my friend, this
really sounds unbelievable.

00:07:43.090 --> 00:07:48.160
And I said, like the doctor
said, I can always be filleted.

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:49.700
I'll just try it.

00:07:49.700 --> 00:07:54.280
So we drove down the coast from
Seattle and stayed in a motel

00:07:54.280 --> 00:07:56.390
at night.

00:07:56.390 --> 00:07:58.860
And that night, I
actually did some

00:07:58.860 --> 00:08:01.700
of this so-called
creative writing.

00:08:01.700 --> 00:08:08.600
And I woke up the next
morning, and the pain

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:10.940
I had been feeling, which--

00:08:10.940 --> 00:08:12.830
maybe I should back up a little.

00:08:12.830 --> 00:08:14.300
When you live with
pain like this,

00:08:14.300 --> 00:08:15.758
it's like you have
a leech attached

00:08:15.758 --> 00:08:19.340
to your body or a monkey on your
back that you can't get rid of.

00:08:19.340 --> 00:08:21.350
It's always there.

00:08:21.350 --> 00:08:24.360
You're always thinking about it.

00:08:24.360 --> 00:08:27.710
You don't realize,
but it preoccupies

00:08:27.710 --> 00:08:29.800
every aspect of your being.

00:08:29.800 --> 00:08:32.960
I woke up that morning after
doing this first session

00:08:32.960 --> 00:08:33.870
of creative writing.

00:08:33.870 --> 00:08:36.890
And the first thing I
noticed is that I didn't

00:08:36.890 --> 00:08:41.750
have that monkey, that leech.

00:08:41.750 --> 00:08:44.670
And at first, I'd
forgotten I'd even

00:08:44.670 --> 00:08:47.070
done the negative writing,
or the creative writing,

00:08:47.070 --> 00:08:48.730
the night before.

00:08:48.730 --> 00:08:51.972
And I thought what's
going on here?

00:08:51.972 --> 00:08:52.935
This is great.

00:08:52.935 --> 00:08:53.655
It still hurts.

00:08:53.655 --> 00:08:56.510
But it's nothing like it was.

00:08:56.510 --> 00:09:00.170
To make a long story short,
after another 24 hours,

00:09:00.170 --> 00:09:06.750
I was 85% pain
free, 85% pain free.

00:09:06.750 --> 00:09:13.220
And today, what, three
years later more or less,

00:09:13.220 --> 00:09:14.740
yes, I have pain.

00:09:14.740 --> 00:09:18.700
But it's pain that's easily
controllable with a Tylenol.

00:09:18.700 --> 00:09:21.210
And sometimes I'll go
through three weeks or more

00:09:21.210 --> 00:09:23.976
without even taking a Tylenol.

00:09:23.976 --> 00:09:28.860
And I'm living a reasonably
normal life, a fairly active

00:09:28.860 --> 00:09:33.486
life-- riding horses,
chainsawing and cutting wood,

00:09:33.486 --> 00:09:35.595
again, doing physical things.

00:09:35.595 --> 00:09:36.560
[ENGINE ROARS]

00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:38.470
And they do make my
back uncomfortable.

00:09:38.470 --> 00:09:42.510
But I don't have this
debilitating, crippling pain.

00:09:42.510 --> 00:09:47.910
Basically, by visiting Dr.
Hanscom, I got my life back.

00:09:47.910 --> 00:09:51.389
[END PLAYBACK]

00:10:01.080 --> 00:10:02.830
DAVID HANSCOM: I mean,
he had chronic pain

00:10:02.830 --> 00:10:05.170
for nine solid years.

00:10:05.170 --> 00:10:08.100
He had sought every
imaginable cure possible.

00:10:08.100 --> 00:10:10.120
He had seen over 30 physicians.

00:10:10.120 --> 00:10:12.640
He had two high level
surgeons recommend a fusion

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:14.800
from his neck to his pelvis.

00:10:14.800 --> 00:10:17.950
The complication rate of
that operation is about 70%

00:10:17.950 --> 00:10:19.565
with half of those being major.

00:10:19.565 --> 00:10:21.940
The chance of actually solving
his pain with that surgery

00:10:21.940 --> 00:10:24.560
is about 20% to 25%.

00:10:24.560 --> 00:10:27.100
So within six weeks,
he was pain free.

00:10:27.100 --> 00:10:29.890
He and I have become good
friends along with my wife.

00:10:29.890 --> 00:10:31.390
And he's fine.

00:10:31.390 --> 00:10:33.130
He lives a normal life.

00:10:33.130 --> 00:10:35.950
And if any of us did half the
work that he did at age 72,

00:10:35.950 --> 00:10:37.510
our backs would be killing us.

00:10:37.510 --> 00:10:39.640
He's fine.

00:10:39.640 --> 00:10:42.310
So visualize what his
life would have been like

00:10:42.310 --> 00:10:47.516
if he'd had that 12 hours of
surgery, high dose narcotics.

00:10:47.516 --> 00:10:48.890
It would have been
a big problem.

00:11:13.870 --> 00:11:17.700
So the purpose of my
talk today is to show you

00:11:17.700 --> 00:11:20.070
that this is not magic.

00:11:20.070 --> 00:11:21.940
This is not a belief system.

00:11:21.940 --> 00:11:24.600
This is basically every human
being has their own capacity

00:11:24.600 --> 00:11:26.610
to heal, every one of us.

00:11:26.610 --> 00:11:29.990
From an evolutionary standpoint,
that would make sense, right?

00:11:29.990 --> 00:11:34.529
The key is Mark somehow quickly
found his capacity to heal.

00:11:34.529 --> 00:11:35.820
I hear this story all the time.

00:11:35.820 --> 00:11:37.514
This is not an unusual story.

00:11:37.514 --> 00:11:39.430
I've watched hundreds
and hundreds of patients

00:11:39.430 --> 00:11:41.860
go to pain free, not
managing the pain,

00:11:41.860 --> 00:11:44.940
but actually solving the pain.

00:11:44.940 --> 00:11:46.305
So it is my belief--

00:11:52.230 --> 00:11:53.740
and I'm sort of a technophobe.

00:11:53.740 --> 00:11:56.440
I have to tell you this.

00:11:56.440 --> 00:11:58.610
But I believe that one of
the most basic needs that

00:11:58.610 --> 00:12:01.080
makes us human is to be
in charge of our destiny

00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:02.474
with a sense of worth.

00:12:02.474 --> 00:12:04.890
Successfully treating patients
suffering from chronic pain

00:12:04.890 --> 00:12:07.770
requires reconnecting them with
their vision and their purpose

00:12:07.770 --> 00:12:08.910
in life.

00:12:08.910 --> 00:12:10.710
When you're in chronic
pain and suffering,

00:12:10.710 --> 00:12:12.615
you become completely
disconnected.

00:12:17.740 --> 00:12:20.350
So what happened to Mark?

00:12:20.350 --> 00:12:23.650
So as a physician, when we
walk into the office, when

00:12:23.650 --> 00:12:26.070
we give lectures ever
since I've been a resident,

00:12:26.070 --> 00:12:28.400
there is quote,
"the ideal patient."

00:12:28.400 --> 00:12:30.090
That means they're employed.

00:12:30.090 --> 00:12:32.140
They're not on disability.

00:12:32.140 --> 00:12:32.890
They're motivated.

00:12:32.890 --> 00:12:33.370
They're smart.

00:12:33.370 --> 00:12:34.203
They're intelligent.

00:12:34.203 --> 00:12:35.170
He was all of those.

00:12:35.170 --> 00:12:36.620
OK?

00:12:36.620 --> 00:12:38.582
What happened?

00:12:38.582 --> 00:12:40.290
And so what we do as
surgeons-- we think,

00:12:40.290 --> 00:12:42.081
well, we can figure
this out in the clinic.

00:12:42.081 --> 00:12:44.525
But remember, we're
on a volume schedule.

00:12:44.525 --> 00:12:46.100
We're in a busy clinic.

00:12:46.100 --> 00:12:48.980
We have 10 to 15 minutes,
maybe half an hour at the most.

00:12:48.980 --> 00:12:52.160
And remember, two surgeons made
a diagnosis, a recommendation,

00:12:52.160 --> 00:12:56.431
for a 12-hour surgery on the
first visit, the first visit.

00:12:56.431 --> 00:12:56.930
OK?

00:12:56.930 --> 00:12:59.240
That's a big deal.

00:12:59.240 --> 00:13:03.410
Sach had recommendations
for surgery for back pain.

00:13:03.410 --> 00:13:06.139
Were this on the first
visit also many times?

00:13:06.139 --> 00:13:07.930
And often patients come
to me saying, well,

00:13:07.930 --> 00:13:10.420
their surgeons really had an
urgency to do this operation.

00:13:10.420 --> 00:13:14.670
They try to sign them up
right there in the office.

00:13:14.670 --> 00:13:16.932
So the research has two
papers-- this is one of them--

00:13:16.932 --> 00:13:18.390
where surgeons
actually-- it's been

00:13:18.390 --> 00:13:22.590
documented that surgeons have a
limited ability to assess risk.

00:13:22.590 --> 00:13:25.410
So the DRAM is a risk
assessment score--

00:13:25.410 --> 00:13:28.180
Depression, Anxiety, which
is called somatization, where

00:13:28.180 --> 00:13:30.300
you can't focus on your body.

00:13:30.300 --> 00:13:32.670
