So the chemical consequences
of being trapped are high.

00:24:41.710 --> 00:24:44.980
Remember, each organ system
secretes its own chemicals.

00:24:44.980 --> 00:24:47.700
Each organ system's going
to respond in its own way.

00:24:47.700 --> 00:24:49.200
That's why there's
so many symptoms.

00:24:52.640 --> 00:24:53.894
So what happened to Mark?

00:24:53.894 --> 00:24:56.060
OK, so normally, it sounds
like it'd be operational.

00:24:56.060 --> 00:24:57.020
He broke his back.

00:24:57.020 --> 00:24:58.910
He got thrown from a horse.

00:24:58.910 --> 00:25:02.630
He almost froze to death the
night before, et cetera, right?

00:25:02.630 --> 00:25:04.796
So it sounds like, well,
you know chronic pain could

00:25:04.796 --> 00:25:07.150
be sort of logical, right?

00:25:07.150 --> 00:25:08.110
No?

00:25:08.110 --> 00:25:09.730
Big injury, big surgery.

00:25:09.730 --> 00:25:12.220
So I do this surgery every week.

00:25:12.220 --> 00:25:15.040
The normal post-operative
course is two days

00:25:15.040 --> 00:25:17.490
of misery, a week in between.

00:25:17.490 --> 00:25:21.460
By two weeks, the surgical pain
is gone, and by three months,

00:25:21.460 --> 00:25:23.142
people are fine.

00:25:23.142 --> 00:25:25.600
So you see the bruising on his
side there from broken ribs.

00:25:25.600 --> 00:25:28.210
He's got a nicely
healed surgical scar.

00:25:28.210 --> 00:25:31.750
So if this had happened
20 years earlier,

00:25:31.750 --> 00:25:33.670
the chances of him
going into chronic pain

00:25:33.670 --> 00:25:35.290
would have been almost zero.

00:25:35.290 --> 00:25:38.140
This is not the normal
post-operative course.

00:25:38.140 --> 00:25:39.835
So what happened?

00:25:39.835 --> 00:25:42.210
So there's a paper out of
Chicago, which was fascinating.

00:25:42.210 --> 00:25:46.770
It was published in 2013.

00:25:46.770 --> 00:25:48.780
They took a group of volunteers.

00:25:48.780 --> 00:25:51.270
They did these research
MRI scans on the brain.

00:25:51.270 --> 00:25:54.030
They found out
that with back pain

00:25:54.030 --> 00:25:56.910
that there's a certain part
of the brain that lights up

00:25:56.910 --> 00:25:58.390
every time, consistent.

00:25:58.390 --> 00:26:01.270
It's called the
nociceptive center.

00:26:01.270 --> 00:26:03.140
So they took patients,
or volunteers,

00:26:03.140 --> 00:26:05.115
who had back pain for
less than two months.

00:26:05.115 --> 00:26:07.931
And they saw that the pain
center lit up like it should.

00:26:07.931 --> 00:26:09.680
Then they took people
who had chronic back

00:26:09.680 --> 00:26:12.980
for more than 10 years, and
the pain center was quiet.

00:26:12.980 --> 00:26:15.230
There's no activity in the
pain center on these people

00:26:15.230 --> 00:26:17.390
with chronic back pain.

00:26:17.390 --> 00:26:20.150
Guess where the center
of activity was?

00:26:20.150 --> 00:26:21.890
There's an emotional center.

00:26:21.890 --> 00:26:24.674
And it completely shifted
from the emotional center--

00:26:24.674 --> 00:26:26.840
sorry-- from the pain center
to the emotional center

00:26:26.840 --> 00:26:28.203
in about 12 months.

00:26:28.203 --> 00:26:31.460
It happened to every
patient, every time.

00:26:31.460 --> 00:26:33.250
So we all know about
phantom limb pain,

00:26:33.250 --> 00:26:34.765
which is fascinating.

00:26:34.765 --> 00:26:36.670
And from medical school
on, it's been sort of

00:26:36.670 --> 00:26:38.380
glossed over in my training.

00:26:38.380 --> 00:26:39.970
This is a big deal.

00:26:39.970 --> 00:26:41.110
I'm an orthopedic surgeon.

00:26:41.110 --> 00:26:42.760
I've done many amputations.

00:26:42.760 --> 00:26:45.400
It's sort of a disturbing
process to take a limb

00:26:45.400 --> 00:26:46.810
and put it into a bucket.

00:26:46.810 --> 00:26:48.570
So you know where the
pain's coming from.

00:26:48.570 --> 00:26:50.560
It's completely gone.

00:26:50.560 --> 00:26:54.770
Over half the patients feel the
leg, and they feel the pain.

00:26:54.770 --> 00:26:56.290
What's wrong with that picture?

00:26:56.290 --> 00:26:58.720
That's a big deal.

00:26:58.720 --> 00:27:00.720
So what happens is that
the pain is still there,

00:27:00.720 --> 00:27:02.094
with the back
pain, for instance.

00:27:02.094 --> 00:27:04.230
But again, it can happen
in any part of the body.

00:27:04.230 --> 00:27:08.370
The pain is still there,
but it's a different driver.

00:27:08.370 --> 00:27:10.260
So instead of being
the pain center,

00:27:10.260 --> 00:27:12.930
it's now the emotional center.

00:27:12.930 --> 00:27:14.610
The other thing I
illustrate a lot with

00:27:14.610 --> 00:27:18.681
is that when you turn a light
switch on, where's the light?

00:27:18.681 --> 00:27:19.430
It's at the light.

00:27:19.430 --> 00:27:20.430
It's not at the switch.

00:27:20.430 --> 00:27:21.270
Right?

00:27:21.270 --> 00:27:22.410
So when the pain
center in the brain

00:27:22.410 --> 00:27:25.034
is turned on, whether it's from
an emotional source in the pain

00:27:25.034 --> 00:27:28.300
center, the pain is going to
be here, not in your brain.

00:27:31.250 --> 00:27:36.050
So we know there's plenty of
risk factors for poor outcomes.

00:27:36.050 --> 00:27:39.580
There is younger
age, being female,

00:27:39.580 --> 00:27:43.030
the length of the pain,
the severity of the injury,

00:27:43.030 --> 00:27:46.120
anxiety, depression,
catastrophizing, fear

00:27:46.120 --> 00:27:48.770
avoidance, high dose narcotics.

00:27:48.770 --> 00:27:52.360
All those are major risk--
oh, sleep, that's a huge one.

00:27:52.360 --> 00:27:55.667
Those are all major risk factors
for poor surgical outcomes.

00:27:55.667 --> 00:27:57.250
And I've known that
for over 30 years.

00:27:57.250 --> 00:27:59.560
This has been in the medical
literature for over 60 years.

00:27:59.560 --> 00:28:00.800
It's been there a long time.

00:28:00.800 --> 00:28:01.732
We know this.

00:28:01.732 --> 00:28:03.190
From medical school
on, we're told,

00:28:03.190 --> 00:28:05.500
if you take a patient
who's stressed out--

00:28:05.500 --> 00:28:07.709
they don't talk about the
body chemistry, by the way.

00:28:07.709 --> 00:28:08.958
By they way, I'm just curious.

00:28:08.958 --> 00:28:11.130
How people learned about
adrenaline in high school?

00:28:11.130 --> 00:28:11.690
Can you raise your hands?

00:28:11.690 --> 00:28:12.410
I'm just curious.

00:28:12.410 --> 00:28:13.070
OK.

00:28:13.070 --> 00:28:15.500
So that, to me, that's
why I'm a little perplexed

00:28:15.500 --> 00:28:17.340
that the medical
system has missed this

00:28:17.340 --> 00:28:19.340
because when you're under
stress for any reason,

00:28:19.340 --> 00:28:21.920
your body's full of adrenaline.

00:28:21.920 --> 00:28:25.370
So the research paper out of
Baltimore showed that only 10%

00:28:25.370 --> 00:28:28.046
of orthopedic surgeons
and neurosurgeons

00:28:28.046 --> 00:28:29.420
were assessing
these risk factors

00:28:29.420 --> 00:28:31.550
before they did surgery.

00:28:31.550 --> 00:28:32.552
And guess what?

00:28:32.552 --> 00:28:34.010
The outcomes were
all over the map.

00:28:34.010 --> 00:28:35.510
In fact, the outcomes
were very bad

00:28:35.510 --> 00:28:38.251
when these risk factors
weren't addressed.

00:28:44.640 --> 00:28:46.970
So the definition of
chronic pain, now--

00:28:46.970 --> 00:28:50.180
this is from Chicago,
but neuroscience centers

00:28:50.180 --> 00:28:53.100
around the world have come
to this common definition

00:28:53.100 --> 00:28:55.370
that chronic pain is an
"imbedded memory that

00:28:55.370 --> 00:28:58.970
becomes linked with more
and more life experiences,

00:28:58.970 --> 00:29:00.395
and the memory can't be erased."

00:29:02.372 --> 00:29:04.330
And there's another saying
that neuroscientists

00:29:04.330 --> 00:29:07.130
have that neurons that fire
together wire together.

00:29:07.130 --> 00:29:10.120
So if you have back
pain when you climbed

00:29:10.120 --> 00:29:13.000
a certain set of steps,
again, every time you

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:17.574
climb those steps, your
brain links that with pain.

00:29:17.574 --> 00:29:18.990
So this is not
psychological, this

00:29:18.990 --> 00:29:21.535
is simply a direct link
with a chemical response.

00:29:21.535 --> 00:29:25.210
It has nothing to
do with psychology.

00:29:25.210 --> 00:29:28.690
So again, I'm going to ask
people to raise their hands.

00:29:28.690 --> 00:29:30.790
How many people
are given the idea

00:29:30.790 --> 00:29:32.710
that surgery is the
definitive solution?

00:29:32.710 --> 00:29:34.960
Is that a common belief
amongst this crowd?

00:29:34.960 --> 00:29:36.640
A little bit.

00:29:36.640 --> 00:29:37.776
So in doctors, it is.

00:29:37.776 --> 00:29:40.276
I mean, when I first started
my training for the first seven

00:29:40.276 --> 00:29:42.220
or eight years, I felt
like as a surgeon,

00:29:42.220 --> 00:29:43.690
you've suffered for a long time.

00:29:43.690 --> 00:29:46.180
I felt obligated,
literally obligated,

00:29:46.180 --> 00:29:47.990
to find a solution
to your problem.

00:29:47.990 --> 00:29:49.690
What else do you do?

00:29:49.690 --> 00:29:50.960
You've tried everything else.

00:29:50.960 --> 00:29:53.685
And so no matter
what happens, you're

00:29:53.685 --> 00:29:55.810
going to try to find a
reason to solve the problem.

00:29:55.810 --> 00:29:57.630
Right?

00:29:57.630 --> 00:30:00.670
Well, really?

00:30:00.670 --> 00:30:03.890
So here's some of the data.

00:30:03.890 --> 00:30:07.750
So the problem is, you're
using a structural solution

00:30:07.750 --> 00:30:09.590
for a neurological diagnosis.

00:30:09.590 --> 00:30:11.210
You're way off target.

00:30:11.210 --> 00:30:12.310
It can't work.

00:30:12.310 --> 00:30:13.180
It just can't work.

00:30:13.180 --> 00:30:13.804
And guess what?

00:30:13.804 --> 00:30:16.380
It doesn't work.

00:30:16.380 --> 00:30:21.300
So the analogy I like to use is
that I'm going to the dentist

00:30:21.300 --> 00:30:23.910
with a cavity that's painful.

00:30:23.910 --> 00:30:25.170
You know where the problem is.

00:30:25.170 --> 00:30:27.060
The dentist either
pulls the tooth

00:30:27.060 --> 00:30:28.770
or fills the cavity or crown.

00:30:28.770 --> 00:30:29.460
Problem solved.

00:30:29.460 --> 00:30:29.959
Right?

00:30:29.959 --> 00:30:32.700
Happens almost 100% of the time.

00:30:32.700 --> 00:30:35.324
But if you go to the
dentist with mouth pain,

00:30:35.324 --> 00:30:36.990
and you don't know
where the problem is,

00:30:36.990 --> 00:30:39.060
and you start filling
teeth, pulling teeth,

00:30:39.060 --> 00:30:43.020
whatever, the chances of
success are very, very low.

00:30:43.020 --> 00:30:45.360
With back pain, we
actually don't know

00:30:45.360 --> 00:30:46.524
where the pain coming from.

00:30:46.524 --> 00:30:48.440
We know where the pain's
coming from literally

00:30:48.440 --> 00:30:51.680
15% of the time, 1-5.

00:30:51.680 --> 00:30:54.232
So you start doing these
big procedures on something

00:30:54.232 --> 00:30:55.940
that you don't know
what the solution is.

00:30:55.940 --> 00:30:58.000
Spine surgery has a
terrible reputation.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:00.570
And it actually is deserved.

00:31:00.570 --> 00:31:03.380
So surgery works extremely
well for a structural problem.

00:31:03.380 --> 00:31:04.700
I do lots of surgery.

00:31:04.700 --> 00:31:07.200
We have a high success rate,
but I can see what we're doing.

00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:10.480
You can't fix something
you can't see.

00:31:10.480 --> 00:31:12.230
What I didn't know
until a few years ago--

00:31:12.230 --> 00:31:14.654
and this data has actually
been around for a while--

00:31:14.654 --> 00:31:17.070
is that when you have chronic
pain in your nervous system,

00:31:17.070 --> 00:31:20.040
and you do surgery in
another part of the body,

00:31:20.040 --> 00:31:25.072
you can create chronic
pain in the new body part.

00:31:25.072 --> 00:31:26.780
So let's take our
hernia repair, which is

00:31:26.780 --> 00:31:28.360
a very straightforward surgery.

00:31:28.360 --> 00:31:30.620
And say you've had chronic
neck pain for five years.

00:31:30.620 --> 00:31:32.540
The hernia goes beautifully.

00:31:32.540 --> 00:31:34.580
You can induce chronic
pain at the hernia site

00:31:34.580 --> 00:31:37.360
between 5% to 60% of the time.

00:31:37.360 --> 00:31:41.780
And up to 4% of the time,
it can become permanent.

00:31:41.780 --> 00:31:43.160
Surgeons aren't taught this.

00:31:43.160 --> 00:31:44.150
I wasn't.

00:31:44.150 --> 00:31:46.400
Patients aren't really
told that chronic pain

00:31:46.400 --> 00:31:49.230
can be a complication of a
simple, well-performed surgery.

00:31:49.230 --> 00:31:50.280
And it's a big deal.

00:31:53.670 --> 00:31:57.615
So in defense of
the surgeons, when

00:31:57.615 --> 00:31:59.760
we talk about a
Blue Plate Special,

00:31:59.760 --> 00:32:02.740
that's all we're trained to do.

00:32:02.740 --> 00:32:05.360
And we're not really
taught about chronic pain.

00:32:05.360 --> 00:32:07.000
We're not taught
about sleep, stress.

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:08.950
Actually, we sort
of know about it.

00:32:08.950 --> 00:32:11.220
But then surgeons, the way
we become compartmentalized

00:32:11.220 --> 00:32:14.160
as specialists, we're
responsible for this part

00:32:14.160 --> 00:32:16.440
of the problem, but not the
whole part of the problem.

00:32:16.440 --> 00:32:18.250
And so there's been
a real disconnect.

00:32:18.250 --> 00:32:20.789
So the physicians
are well-intentioned,

00:32:20.789 --> 00:32:23.080
but the business of medicine
has made it very difficult

00:32:23.080 --> 00:32:25.180
for us to actually take
time to talk to and listen

00:32:25.180 --> 00:32:27.400
to the patients.

00:32:27.400 --> 00:32:32.440
So with Mark's situation, I will
admit that that first visit,

00:32:32.440 --> 00:32:35.200
I did not know his background.

00:32:35.200 --> 00:32:37.210
But it was easy for him
because I never, ever

00:32:37.210 --> 00:32:39.520
make a surgical decision
on the first visit, ever.

00:32:39.520 --> 00:32:40.330
I don't know you.

00:32:40.330 --> 00:32:41.260
You don't know me.

00:32:41.260 --> 00:32:42.790
I don't know the circumstances.

00:32:42.790 --> 00:32:45.094
The last 10 years,
I have learned a lot

00:32:45.094 --> 00:32:46.510
that when people
are under stress,

00:32:46.510 --> 00:32:48.550
the body chemistry
changes, and symptoms

00:32:48.550 --> 00:32:50.959
start arising that
had not arisen before.

00:32:50.959 --> 00:32:52.750
So with Mark, it was
actually pretty simple

00:32:52.750 --> 00:32:56.290
because he did not
have a surgical lesion.

00:32:56.290 --> 00:32:59.980
How many people here have been
told that degenerative disc

00:32:59.980 --> 00:33:01.220
disease is a problem?

00:33:01.220 --> 00:33:02.530
Anybody heard that?

00:33:02.530 --> 00:33:03.790
OK.

00:33:03.790 --> 00:33:06.530
So we don't know where back pain
comes from most of the time.

00:33:06.530 --> 00:33:08.980
But we actually know--

00:33:08.980 --> 00:33:11.800
it's been well-documented--
that arthritis,

00:33:11.800 --> 00:33:14.830
bulging disc, herniated
disc, degenerative

00:33:14.830 --> 00:33:16.800
disc actually don't cause pain.

00:33:16.800 --> 00:33:19.060
They are not a source of pain.

00:33:19.060 --> 00:33:20.538
Is that surprising to anybody?

00:33:23.170 --> 00:33:25.360
It's a problem because
your spine becomes stiffer.

00:33:28.135 --> 00:33:30.310
But it's been well-documented
that it is not

00:33:30.310 --> 00:33:32.460
a source of pain yet.

00:33:32.460 --> 00:33:37.110
It is a reason to do surgery
on over 500,000 people per year

00:33:37.110 --> 00:33:38.360
right now.

00:33:38.360 --> 00:33:40.140
They estimate by
2020, it will be

00:33:40.140 --> 00:33:42.844
up over a million people per
year getting spine fusions.

00:33:42.844 --> 00:33:44.010
So with Mark, it was simple.

00:33:44.010 --> 00:33:45.630
He's got some disc degeneration.

00:33:45.630 --> 00:33:48.060
He had some arthritis
here, here, here, and here.

00:33:48.060 --> 00:33:50.330
Here's his rods down
in through here.

00:33:50.330 --> 00:33:54.120
Let me just point up to there.

00:33:54.120 --> 00:33:54.933
There's no real--

00:33:58.550 --> 00:34:01.160
Anyway, he has his
arthritis on left side.

00:34:01.160 --> 00:34:03.140
He's got some
narrowing of the disc.

00:34:03.140 --> 00:34:03.809
And that's fine.

00:34:03.809 --> 00:34:05.600
So that's a normal
spine for somebody who's

00:34:05.600 --> 00:34:07.535
68 years old, flat-out normal.

00:34:07.535 --> 00:34:11.861
OK, if anyone of you had a MRI
scan of your spine, especially

00:34:11.861 --> 00:34:14.110
those without pain, you're
going to have degeneration.

00:34:14.110 --> 00:34:16.560
It is not a source of pain.

00:34:16.560 --> 00:34:18.659
So Mark's case was
pretty simple for me.

00:34:18.659 --> 00:34:20.420
So I'm just picking
one study out of many.

00:34:20.420 --> 00:34:22.730
This was done in 2006
out of Stanford here.

00:34:22.730 --> 00:34:25.159
They took patients who had
an unstable spine, actually

00:34:25.159 --> 00:34:27.770
moving back and forth
about 4 millimeters, what

00:34:27.770 --> 00:34:31.310
surgeons consider a source
of pain, and they fused them.

00:34:31.310 --> 00:34:34.380
They found out the
success rate was 72%

00:34:34.380 --> 00:34:37.415
at two years, which, to me,
is lower than it should be.

00:34:37.415 --> 00:34:39.380
To me, it should be 100%.

00:34:39.380 --> 00:34:41.060
But then they did
this disc study,

00:34:41.060 --> 00:34:42.230
where they inject a
dye into the disc.

00:34:42.230 --> 00:34:44.389
If the disc was painful,
then they would fuse it.

00:34:44.389 --> 00:34:46.150
They did one level fusions.

00:34:46.150 --> 00:34:50.880
They found out the success
rate was 27% percent.

00:34:50.880 --> 00:34:54.000
Other papers show 15%, 22%, 24%.

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:56.199
There's not one
paper, not one paper

00:34:56.199 --> 00:34:58.840
that says that a fusion
works for back pain.

00:34:58.840 --> 00:35:00.530
Not one.

00:35:00.530 --> 00:35:04.040
Surgery now is a $13
billion a year industry.

00:35:08.850 --> 00:35:11.910
So I stopped doing surgery
in 1993 for back pain.

00:35:11.910 --> 00:35:14.460
I quit doing fusion
for back pain in 1993.

00:35:14.460 --> 00:35:15.680
But I didn't know what to do.

00:35:15.680 --> 00:35:16.221
What do I do?

00:35:16.221 --> 00:35:17.250
So I was a surgeon.

00:35:17.250 --> 00:35:18.420
I was trained to do fusions.

00:35:18.420 --> 00:35:21.870
I felt guilty if I didn't find
a reason to do the fusion.

00:35:21.870 --> 00:35:24.100
And so what happened, I
learned it the hard way.

00:35:24.100 --> 00:35:28.770
So I became a chronic pain
sufferer for over 15 years.

00:35:28.770 --> 00:35:30.750
That's how this book
evolved was my own ordeal

00:35:30.750 --> 00:35:32.700
with chronic pain.

00:35:32.700 --> 00:35:36.900
And I had 16 of those
symptoms I mentioned before.

00:35:36.900 --> 00:35:39.420
I had ringing in my ears,
burning feet, skin rashes,

00:35:39.420 --> 00:35:41.820
itching scalp,
insomnia, anxiety, OCD.

00:35:41.820 --> 00:35:43.410
You name it, I had it.

00:35:43.410 --> 00:35:45.940
I had no idea what
was going on, no idea.

00:35:45.940 --> 00:35:47.800
And nobody could tell me.

00:35:47.800 --> 00:35:48.810
So I became desperate.

00:35:48.810 --> 00:35:50.040
I had no hope.

00:35:50.040 --> 00:35:52.180
I didn't know what was going on.

00:35:52.180 --> 00:35:54.707
And by pure luck, I ran
across this recommendation

00:35:54.707 --> 00:35:56.790
by Dr. David Burns-- here
at Stanford, by the way.

00:35:56.790 --> 00:35:59.130
And he and I have become
pretty good friends.

00:35:59.130 --> 00:36:02.830
And Jeff has been nice enough
to introduce me to him again.

00:36:02.830 --> 00:36:05.170
David Burns wrote a book
called "Feeling Good."

00:36:05.170 --> 00:36:08.110
And David Burns said
to start writing.

00:36:08.110 --> 00:36:10.160
So I started writing
his technique.

00:36:10.160 --> 00:36:13.710
And I initially thought it was
the book, but I later found out

00:36:13.710 --> 00:36:15.510
was actually the writing.

00:36:15.510 --> 00:36:18.420
There's over 300 research
papers that document

00:36:18.420 --> 00:36:21.600
that expressive writing,
different forms of it, work.

00:36:21.600 --> 00:36:24.750
They break up all
sorts of pain cycles.

00:36:24.750 --> 00:36:25.860
Performance goes up.

00:36:25.860 --> 00:36:26.930
Grades go up.

00:36:26.930 --> 00:36:28.140
Asthma improves.

00:36:28.140 --> 00:36:29.250
Skin heals faster.

00:36:29.250 --> 00:36:30.180
It's unbelievable.

00:36:30.180 --> 00:36:32.250
And nobody knows why it works.

00:36:32.250 --> 00:36:33.630
But there's way
more data on this

00:36:33.630 --> 00:36:37.380
than there is on spine surgery.

00:36:37.380 --> 00:36:40.042
So basically, it's
on my website.

00:36:40.042 --> 00:36:42.250
You simply write down your
thoughts and tear them up.

00:36:42.250 --> 00:36:44.150
And you tear them
up for two reasons.

00:36:44.150 --> 00:36:46.410
First of all, you can't
not control your thoughts,

00:36:46.410 --> 00:36:47.802
but you can separate from them.

00:36:47.802 --> 00:36:50.260
You've heard the philosophers
say for centuries that you're

00:36:50.260 --> 00:36:53.534
not your thoughts, and they
use meditation to separate.

00:36:53.534 --> 00:36:55.200
I call this mechanical
meditation, where

00:36:55.200 --> 00:36:57.040
you write down your thoughts.

00:36:57.040 --> 00:36:59.280
There's a space between
you and your thoughts.

00:36:59.280 --> 00:37:02.250
That space is now connected
with vision and feel, which is

00:37:02.250 --> 00:37:04.181
part of the unconscious brain.

00:37:04.181 --> 00:37:06.430
And the reason why you rip
them up is for two reasons.

00:37:06.430 --> 00:37:07.638
One is to write with freedom.

00:37:07.638 --> 00:37:09.972
And by the way, it can be
positive or negative thoughts.

00:37:09.972 --> 00:37:12.304
Most of the research has been
done on negative thoughts,

00:37:12.304 --> 00:37:13.680
but it doesn't really matter.

00:37:13.680 --> 00:37:15.429
But the other reason
that you rip them up,

00:37:15.429 --> 00:37:17.250
which is more important,
is that if you

00:37:17.250 --> 00:37:19.500
want to analyze and
fix these things,

00:37:19.500 --> 00:37:21.900
where is your attention?

00:37:21.900 --> 00:37:24.370
It's on your thoughts.

00:37:24.370 --> 00:37:25.930
So I still do it,
20 years later.

00:37:25.930 --> 00:37:28.580
If I quit doing my
writing exercises,

00:37:28.580 --> 00:37:31.004
the first thing that happens
is my wife asks me, she goes,

00:37:31.004 --> 00:37:32.670
honey, have you been
doing your writing?

00:37:32.670 --> 00:37:33.204
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:33.204 --> 00:37:34.870
Because we tend both
to get a little bit

00:37:34.870 --> 00:37:37.450
snappy when we don't do
it because we get anxious.

00:37:37.450 --> 00:37:38.920
And I don't sleep as well.

00:37:38.920 --> 00:37:40.960
These little skin rashes pop up.

00:37:40.960 --> 00:37:43.570
So about two weeks almost to
the day, if I quit my writing

00:37:43.570 --> 00:37:45.250
exercises, which I
do maybe one or two

00:37:45.250 --> 00:37:46.610
minutes is all it takes--

00:37:46.610 --> 00:37:47.860
it's like brushing your teeth.

00:37:47.860 --> 00:37:50.000
It's really simple.

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:51.375
So with neuroplasticity,
you want

00:37:51.375 --> 00:37:55.534
to do awareness, separation,
then you want to redirect.

00:37:55.534 --> 00:37:57.700
It's like directing a river
into different channels.

00:37:57.700 --> 00:38:00.158
You want to come off the pain
circuits into a different set

00:38:00.158 --> 00:38:00.850
of circuits.

00:38:00.850 --> 00:38:02.980
So it's things like
visualization, good food,

00:38:02.980 --> 00:38:04.550
good wine, good friends.

00:38:04.550 --> 00:38:08.780
Meditation, that's the
re-visualization tool.

00:38:08.780 --> 00:38:13.930
So you have a situation now
where you have chronic pain.

00:38:13.930 --> 00:38:16.030
You have an adrenalized
nervous system.

00:38:16.030 --> 00:38:18.540
You can't escape your thoughts.

00:38:18.540 --> 00:38:20.190
Surgery is not going to work.

00:38:20.190 --> 00:38:22.770
These are permanent pathways.

00:38:22.770 --> 00:38:26.195
Doesn't sound that good, right?

00:38:26.195 --> 00:38:27.570
And the harder
you try to fix it,

00:38:27.570 --> 00:38:30.650
your attention's on the
pathways, it makes it worse.

00:38:30.650 --> 00:38:31.990
So it is a solvable problem.

00:38:31.990 --> 00:38:34.870
But you have to first understand
the traditional ways of solving

00:38:34.870 --> 00:38:37.669
it can't and don't work.

00:38:37.669 --> 00:38:39.460
So I'll just give you
couple of principles.

00:38:43.504 --> 00:38:45.170
So why is chronic
pain so hard to treat?

00:38:45.170 --> 00:38:50.090
Well, again, we're using
a structural intervention

00:38:50.090 --> 00:38:51.495
for a neurological problem.

00:38:51.495 --> 00:38:52.620
So we're treating symptoms.

00:38:52.620 --> 00:38:54.280
We're not treating
the real cause.

00:38:54.280 --> 00:38:57.709
We're doing surgery,
injections, medications.

00:38:57.709 --> 00:38:59.250
And what's fascinating
and disturbing

00:38:59.250 --> 00:39:01.560
both is that most
of interventions

00:39:01.560 --> 00:39:05.550
we do for chronic pain have
been documented not to work.

00:39:05.550 --> 00:39:07.750
There's no data supporting
epidurals for back pain.

00:39:07.750 --> 00:39:11.340
There's no data supporting
facet rhizotomies for back pain.

00:39:11.340 --> 00:39:12.370
We know about opioids.

00:39:12.370 --> 00:39:13.540
That's a big problem.

00:39:13.540 --> 00:39:16.290
So everything we do in the
medical profession right now

00:39:16.290 --> 00:39:18.190
has actually been
documented not to work,

00:39:18.190 --> 00:39:20.370
including spine surgery.

00:39:20.370 --> 00:39:22.249
We don't have the
diagnosis correct.

00:39:22.249 --> 00:39:24.540
Even though that neuroscience
has shown us a diagnosis,

00:39:24.540 --> 00:39:27.070
this has not penetrated
mainstream medical thinking.

00:39:28.942 --> 00:39:30.400
And the other
problem is that we've

00:39:30.400 --> 00:39:33.790
been throwing simplistic
random solutions

00:39:33.790 --> 00:39:35.234
to a complicated problem.

00:39:35.234 --> 00:39:37.900
I know everybody in this room is
used to dealing with complexity

00:39:37.900 --> 00:39:39.191
and trying to solve complexity.

00:39:39.191 --> 00:39:39.692
Right?

00:39:39.692 --> 00:39:41.190
I had a friend of
mine introduced me

00:39:41.190 --> 00:39:42.150
to complexity theory.

00:39:42.150 --> 00:39:44.080
And I'll admit, I
only know the term.

00:39:44.080 --> 00:39:45.560
But chronic pain's complicated.

00:39:45.560 --> 00:39:48.730
There's multiple things
that affect chronic pain.

00:39:48.730 --> 00:39:51.510
So we're randomly throwing this
at it, throwing this at it,

00:39:51.510 --> 00:39:52.630
and it can't work.

00:39:52.630 --> 00:39:54.210
So it's like fighting
a forest fire.

00:39:54.210 --> 00:39:56.530
It takes multiple strategies
to contain this blaze.

00:39:56.530 --> 00:39:57.400
Right?

00:39:57.400 --> 00:39:59.680
A fire hose isn't
going to do it.

00:39:59.680 --> 00:40:01.480
Bulldozers alone
aren't going to do it.

00:40:01.480 --> 00:40:04.170
This is a multi-pronged
approach to solve it.

00:40:04.170 --> 00:40:05.320
And everything counts.

00:40:08.820 --> 00:40:11.560
So what happens with
this relentless thought

00:40:11.560 --> 00:40:14.199
assault, routinely
adrenalized, we

00:40:14.199 --> 00:40:16.490
have these unpleasant thoughts,
the adrenalized nervous

00:40:16.490 --> 00:40:16.990
system--

00:40:19.480 --> 00:40:21.150
and the two strategies
or two principles

00:40:21.150 --> 00:40:23.358
behind solving the problem
is to simply de-adrenalize

00:40:23.358 --> 00:40:24.464
the nervous system.

00:40:24.464 --> 00:40:26.130
So everybody, just
sit back for a second

00:40:26.130 --> 00:40:27.710
and drop your shoulders.

00:40:27.710 --> 00:40:30.170
Just feel the chair you're in.

00:40:30.170 --> 00:40:31.720
That's it.

00:40:31.720 --> 00:40:34.462
So what you've done is you've
simply switched sensory input.

00:40:34.462 --> 00:40:35.920
Instead of being
on racing thoughts

00:40:35.920 --> 00:40:37.570
or unpleasant
sensations, you just

00:40:37.570 --> 00:40:38.830
went to a different sensation.

00:40:38.830 --> 00:40:40.205
That's it, three
to five seconds,

00:40:40.205 --> 00:40:43.120
I call it active meditation
to decrease the adrenaline

00:40:43.120 --> 00:40:44.200
just a little bit.

00:40:44.200 --> 00:40:46.060
You do it repetitively
throughout the day.

00:40:46.060 --> 00:40:47.851
It keeps the adrenaline
levels coming down.

00:40:47.851 --> 00:40:49.630
It eventually becomes
somewhat automatic.

00:40:49.630 --> 00:40:51.920
I like to do it more as
my personal commitment.

00:40:51.920 --> 00:40:54.260
And the other principle
is called neuroplasticity,

00:40:54.260 --> 00:40:55.635
which remember,
I said awareness,

00:40:55.635 --> 00:40:58.120
separation, redirecting, again,
like redirecting your river

00:40:58.120 --> 00:40:59.980
to a different channel.

00:40:59.980 --> 00:41:02.830
And that's awareness,
separation, reprogramming.

00:41:02.830 --> 00:41:05.470
And so that's the
second principle.

00:41:05.470 --> 00:41:07.210
The third one is shifting.

00:41:07.210 --> 00:41:09.080
So pain pathways are permanent.

00:41:09.080 --> 00:41:10.530
You can't solve them.

00:41:10.530 --> 00:41:12.280
So the [INAUDIBLE]
allows you to separate,

00:41:12.280 --> 00:41:17.190
and then you redirect so you
can shift onto play pathways.

00:41:17.190 --> 00:41:21.660
And those of you in chronic
pain probably, I suspect,

00:41:21.660 --> 00:41:23.220
the life isn't
nearly as much fun

00:41:23.220 --> 00:41:25.640
as it used to be before
you had chronic pain.

00:41:25.640 --> 00:41:26.140
Right?

00:41:26.140 --> 00:41:28.000
It's a problem.

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:30.090
So you can't solve chronic
pain because if you

00:41:30.090 --> 00:41:32.310
quit using those
pathways, they start

00:41:32.310 --> 00:41:34.520
to atrophy just like any skill.

00:41:34.520 --> 00:41:37.170
If you start reinforcing the
creative, enjoyable pathways,

00:41:37.170 --> 00:41:38.562
they start to grow.

00:41:38.562 --> 00:41:40.770
At some tipping point, people
come off these pathways

00:41:40.770 --> 00:41:42.820
and go onto the
pleasant pathways.

00:41:42.820 --> 00:41:44.851
It's very, very consistent.

00:41:48.220 --> 00:41:50.700
So what we do, we tend to run
from pain. tend to fight it,

00:41:50.700 --> 00:41:51.540
whatever.

00:41:51.540 --> 00:41:53.050
And the essence
of the problem is

00:41:53.050 --> 00:41:55.740
the more you fight and
try to treat chronic pain

00:41:55.740 --> 00:41:57.574
and just try to
conquer it-- again,

00:41:57.574 --> 00:41:58.740
it's a million-to-one ratio.

00:41:58.740 --> 00:41:59.499
You can't do it.

00:41:59.499 --> 00:42:01.540
You actually give it more
neurological attention.

00:42:01.540 --> 00:42:03.550
And it's a problem.

00:42:03.550 --> 00:42:06.190
So the essence of the solution
is becoming comfortable--

00:42:06.190 --> 00:42:07.320
again, a learned skill--

00:42:07.320 --> 00:42:10.260
with uncomfortable sensations,
whether they're thoughts,

00:42:10.260 --> 00:42:12.180
anxiety, anger.

00:42:12.180 --> 00:42:14.070
You've got to be OK being angry.

00:42:14.070 --> 00:42:16.110
You got to be OK being anxious.

00:42:16.110 --> 00:42:19.140
And you just train your
body just not to react.

00:42:19.140 --> 00:42:21.880
You notice, as you start
decreasing the adrenaline,

00:42:21.880 --> 00:42:24.030
the body's nerve
conduction improves.

00:42:24.030 --> 00:42:25.950
So the anxiety
drops dramatically.

00:42:25.950 --> 00:42:28.560
That's the most fun part of
this process, by the way.

00:42:28.560 --> 00:42:31.510
And then the pain
starts to improve.

00:42:31.510 --> 00:42:35.050
So we call this
the ring of fire.

00:42:35.050 --> 00:42:37.570
We're trained to avoid anxiety.

00:42:37.570 --> 00:42:40.350
So the red ring represents
anger, anxiety, disgust,

00:42:40.350 --> 00:42:41.555
vulnerability, et cetera.

00:42:41.555 --> 00:42:43.094
And we hate it.

00:42:43.094 --> 00:42:44.510
This is a survival
center feeling.

00:42:44.510 --> 00:42:47.020
So what we do is we
spend a lifetime trying

00:42:47.020 --> 00:42:51.010
to achieve, accomplish, own,
experience, whatever it is,

00:42:51.010 --> 00:42:54.550
to stay in this blue ring
to avoid the red ring.

00:42:54.550 --> 00:42:57.749
So look at this when you go
home-- it's on the website--

00:42:57.749 --> 00:42:58.540
and think about it.

00:42:58.540 --> 00:43:01.132
I realized at one point,
I spent my entire life

00:43:01.132 --> 00:43:01.840
in the blue ring.

00:43:01.840 --> 00:43:03.880
And I would touch the red
ring and pop right out

00:43:03.880 --> 00:43:04.830
into the blue ring.

00:43:04.830 --> 00:43:07.080
I was so much in the blue
ring, I actually didn't even

00:43:07.080 --> 00:43:08.690
know the red ring existed.

00:43:08.690 --> 00:43:12.070
So when I, by force, was forced
to go through the red ring

00:43:12.070 --> 00:43:14.980
into the center is you become
comfortable with uncomfortable

00:43:14.980 --> 00:43:19.780
feelings, where you end up is in
the green, which is the center,

00:43:19.780 --> 00:43:21.220
safe, content.

00:43:21.220 --> 00:43:24.140
And you're not
burning adrenaline.

00:43:24.140 --> 00:43:26.840
And I probably have triple the
energy I had in high school,

00:43:26.840 --> 00:43:28.923
and I had plenty back then
because I'm not burning

00:43:28.923 --> 00:43:31.700
adrenaline all the time.

00:43:31.700 --> 00:43:33.440
So we're taught you
can have it all.

00:43:33.440 --> 00:43:34.460
Right?

00:43:34.460 --> 00:43:36.560
We have all these opportunities.

00:43:36.560 --> 00:43:40.010
And the problem is you
cannot run your mind.

00:43:40.010 --> 00:43:42.616
So what we are taught
to do is that we're

00:43:42.616 --> 00:43:44.240
trying to make
ourselves better people,

00:43:44.240 --> 00:43:46.370
and it's like climbing
a huge mountain.

00:43:46.370 --> 00:43:49.370
At the top of this mountain,
there's a better you.

00:43:49.370 --> 00:43:50.810
And so you learn.

00:43:50.810 --> 00:43:51.820
You become enlightened.

00:43:51.820 --> 00:43:52.570
You meditate.

00:43:52.570 --> 00:43:55.170
You do mindfulness,
all this type of stuff,

00:43:55.170 --> 00:43:56.644
but there's no top
to the mountain.

00:43:56.644 --> 00:43:59.060
You tell me you have an ideal
picture of who you should be

00:43:59.060 --> 00:44:00.730
or could be in your
brain, and you're

00:44:00.730 --> 00:44:03.977
climbing and climbing and
climbing, but there's no top.

00:44:03.977 --> 00:44:05.810
So what you do, as
[INAUDIBLE],, if you just

00:44:05.810 --> 00:44:08.290
picture a bunch of balloons
tied to a railing, what

00:44:08.290 --> 00:44:11.900
the tools do, they
cut the strings.

00:44:11.900 --> 00:44:15.957
And pretty soon, you get to
take off, which takes no energy.

00:44:15.957 --> 00:44:16.790
And where do you go?

00:44:16.790 --> 00:44:17.420
There's no place to go.

00:44:17.420 --> 00:44:18.711
You don't have to go any place.

00:44:18.711 --> 00:44:20.740
You're just there.

00:44:20.740 --> 00:44:23.410
And what happens, you
get to be creative again.

00:44:23.410 --> 00:44:26.600
Pain becomes sort
of a distant memory.

00:44:26.600 --> 00:44:28.316
And you're free.

00:44:28.316 --> 00:44:31.430
So you can't solve chronic pain.

00:44:31.430 --> 00:44:33.830
These are permanent,
unconscious survival skills,

00:44:33.830 --> 00:44:37.247
but you can move into
a different realm.

00:44:37.247 --> 00:44:39.455
So the details are all in
my book, "Back in Control--

00:44:39.455 --> 00:44:41.379
a Surgeon's Roadmap
Out of Chronic Pain."

00:44:41.379 --> 00:44:43.670
And I learned this the hard
way, literally a millimeter

00:44:43.670 --> 00:44:44.776
at a time.

00:44:44.776 --> 00:44:46.400
Then the website I
recommend, actually,

00:44:46.400 --> 00:44:49.145
people hop on first and
just go to stage one.

00:44:49.145 --> 00:44:52.410
And you'll see a sequence that,
over the next six to 12 months,

00:44:52.410 --> 00:44:54.500
as you start walking
through this sequence,

00:44:54.500 --> 00:44:56.950
it's not a fixing process.

00:44:56.950 --> 00:44:57.980
It's not a formula.

00:44:57.980 --> 00:45:00.100
It's not a one, two,
three, and you're fixed.

00:45:00.100 --> 00:45:04.460
But it's a set of concepts,
a framework, that breaks pain

00:45:04.460 --> 00:45:06.170
into its different parts.

00:45:06.170 --> 00:45:09.230
It allows you to address
each part on your own terms.

00:45:09.230 --> 00:45:10.139
You take control.

00:45:10.139 --> 00:45:12.680
And there's some tipping points,
and then we go to pain-free.

00:45:12.680 --> 00:45:16.827
And it's very, very consistent.

00:45:16.827 --> 00:45:17.660
Thank you very much.

00:45:17.660 --> 00:45:18.800
Appreciate your time.

