So the answer is yes, it
works for any type of pain.

00:45:54.890 --> 00:45:58.804
What we do, though, we do what
we call a pre-hab process.

00:45:58.804 --> 00:46:00.470
And if you're my
patient, look, maybe we

00:46:00.470 --> 00:46:02.242
do surgery on your back.

00:46:02.242 --> 00:46:03.700
We're going to calm
you down first.

00:46:03.700 --> 00:46:05.640
And our outcomes have
been spectacular.

00:46:05.640 --> 00:46:07.850
So yeah, the
solution-- so actually,

00:46:07.850 --> 00:46:10.820
now, almost 100 patients
that were on the schedule

00:46:10.820 --> 00:46:13.940
to have surgery, they came
in for their final visit,

00:46:13.940 --> 00:46:15.230
they canceled their surgery.

00:46:15.230 --> 00:46:16.505
The pain went away.

00:46:16.505 --> 00:46:18.130
So that has been
completely unexpected.

00:46:18.130 --> 00:46:20.850
So it's actually been
devastating to my practice.

00:46:20.850 --> 00:46:22.475
So it's a little
awkward at this point.

00:46:22.475 --> 00:46:23.849
SACHIT EGAN: That's
good to hear.

00:46:23.849 --> 00:46:25.380
I guess a follow-up
would be-- this

00:46:25.380 --> 00:46:28.470
is something that I
haven't asked you before.

00:46:28.470 --> 00:46:31.160
There's a certain level of
anxiety that's perhaps natural.

00:46:31.160 --> 00:46:33.980
It's not the kind that you
would go see a therapist for,

00:46:33.980 --> 00:46:35.686
that somebody would
say is abnormal.

00:46:35.686 --> 00:46:36.560
DAVID HANSCOM: Right.

00:46:36.560 --> 00:46:38.851
SACHIT EGAN: At what point
do you have a patient maybe,

00:46:38.851 --> 00:46:42.920
and you might not want to do
surgery on them because they

00:46:42.920 --> 00:46:45.680
don't have a problem in their
spine that warrants surgery.

00:46:45.680 --> 00:46:47.449
You can tell that
they're anxious,

00:46:47.449 --> 00:46:48.740
but it's an appropriate amount.

00:46:48.740 --> 00:46:50.281
Like, do you have
something you would

00:46:50.281 --> 00:46:51.890
say to those types of people?

00:46:51.890 --> 00:46:52.310
DAVID HANSCOM:
Well, first of all,

00:46:52.310 --> 00:46:54.360
if you didn't have
anxiety, you would die.

00:46:54.360 --> 00:46:56.420
So this is not about
getting rid of anxiety.

00:46:56.420 --> 00:46:58.080
It's not about
suppressing anxiety.

00:46:58.080 --> 00:47:00.430
It's being comfortable to
use the cues to actually take

00:47:00.430 --> 00:47:01.700
safe action.

00:47:01.700 --> 00:47:03.530
So I mean, there's
no definition of when

00:47:03.530 --> 00:47:05.060
anxiety becomes a problem.

00:47:05.060 --> 00:47:07.630
In other words, if
it's disruptive to you,

00:47:07.630 --> 00:47:08.540
then it's a problem.

00:47:08.540 --> 00:47:09.134
Right?

00:47:09.134 --> 00:47:11.300
So again, it's not trying
to solve it or control it.

00:47:11.300 --> 00:47:12.820
It's simply letting it go.

00:47:12.820 --> 00:47:15.320
And I talk about moving
forward with your pain, which

00:47:15.320 --> 00:47:15.944
means anxiety.

00:47:15.944 --> 00:47:18.110
By the way, I didn't make
this clear in the lecture.

00:47:18.110 --> 00:47:20.485
Mental pain and physical pain
are processed the same way.

00:47:20.485 --> 00:47:21.950
Anxiety is the pain.

00:47:21.950 --> 00:47:22.827
OK?

00:47:22.827 --> 00:47:24.910
So you're not trying to
get rid of it or solve it.

00:47:24.910 --> 00:47:27.050
But as you quit
paying attention to it

00:47:27.050 --> 00:47:30.740
and trying to do battle with
it, it simply starts to atrophy.

00:47:30.740 --> 00:47:32.830
And so yeah, anxiety is
something that's life.

00:47:32.830 --> 00:47:33.704
Anger's part of life.

00:47:33.704 --> 00:47:35.280
You're not going
to get rid of that.

00:47:35.280 --> 00:47:36.238
SACHIT EGAN: Thank you.

00:47:38.456 --> 00:47:42.195
AUDIENCE: Hi, your
comments about adrenaline

00:47:42.195 --> 00:47:44.320
makes me reall curious,
because from my experience,

00:47:44.320 --> 00:47:46.420
I've found that
adrenaline actually

00:47:46.420 --> 00:47:52.360
helps with the pain in the sense
that it washes it out or makes

00:47:52.360 --> 00:47:53.800
me forget about it.

00:47:53.800 --> 00:47:56.406
Is that because I'm on
the blue ring, let's say?

00:47:56.406 --> 00:47:57.258
DAVID HANSCOM: Yep.

00:47:57.258 --> 00:47:58.540
AUDIENCE: There you go.

00:47:58.540 --> 00:48:00.460
DAVID HANSCOM: But let
me talk about that.

00:48:00.460 --> 00:48:02.230
I mean, 20 years ago, I
had a patient come in who,

00:48:02.230 --> 00:48:03.438
we'd talk about this process.

00:48:03.438 --> 00:48:04.960
I didn't have a
project back then,

00:48:04.960 --> 00:48:06.220
but I had some
sense that there's

00:48:06.220 --> 00:48:07.310
some things going on here.

00:48:07.310 --> 00:48:08.814
So he was an
incredibly angry guy.

00:48:08.814 --> 00:48:09.730
Not that you're angry.

00:48:09.730 --> 00:48:10.240
I don't know you.

00:48:10.240 --> 00:48:12.200
But let's just take
perfectionism for a second.

00:48:12.200 --> 00:48:14.000
All of us have high
standards, right?

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:16.060
We think that's the
right thing to do.

00:48:16.060 --> 00:48:17.518
Well, the problem
is that genealogy

00:48:17.518 --> 00:48:19.867
of anger, where you have a
situation that you blame,

00:48:19.867 --> 00:48:21.700
that you're a victim,
and then you're angry.

00:48:21.700 --> 00:48:24.540
So with perfectionism, which
is being self-critical,

00:48:24.540 --> 00:48:26.920
you have perfection which
you'll never achieve.

00:48:26.920 --> 00:48:29.370
So you're either unhappy with
the situation or yourself

00:48:29.370 --> 00:48:30.750
of being less than perfect.

00:48:30.750 --> 00:48:32.916
So you're always a victim,
you're always frustrated,

00:48:32.916 --> 00:48:34.972
and you're always
angry, frustrated.

00:48:34.972 --> 00:48:36.430
So Dr. Burns pointed
out the delta,

00:48:36.430 --> 00:48:38.620
or the difference
between reality

00:48:38.620 --> 00:48:40.886
and your vision of perfection--
sorry-- your vision

00:48:40.886 --> 00:48:44.240
of perfection and reality is how
unhappy you're going to become.

00:48:44.240 --> 00:48:45.620
So what happens
in that situation

00:48:45.620 --> 00:48:47.130
is you're always adrenalized.

00:48:47.130 --> 00:48:49.450
So what happens is, I used
to be quote, "successful."

00:48:49.450 --> 00:48:50.504
Right?

00:48:50.504 --> 00:48:52.420
I went to the top, top
level spine fellowship.

00:48:52.420 --> 00:48:54.772
I was successful, made
money, had a beautiful house.

00:48:54.772 --> 00:48:56.980
And the same adrenaline drug
that took me up the hill

00:48:56.980 --> 00:48:59.420
took me right down
the other side.

00:48:59.420 --> 00:49:02.870
It's hard to let go of because
we're used to adrenaline.

00:49:02.870 --> 00:49:05.540
It does quote, "make us
successful" on paper.

00:49:05.540 --> 00:49:07.130
I also have 19
medical colleagues

00:49:07.130 --> 00:49:08.600
who died from suicide.

00:49:08.600 --> 00:49:12.050
Doctors have double the suicide
rate of the average population.

00:49:12.050 --> 00:49:13.970
And suicide is not a
depression response.

00:49:13.970 --> 00:49:17.450
It's an anger response
because anger is destructive.

00:49:17.450 --> 00:49:20.840
The ultimate act of destruction
is self-destruction.

00:49:20.840 --> 00:49:24.396
So I can give you hundreds of
stories of most my colleagues,

00:49:24.396 --> 00:49:25.520
of people self-destructing.

00:49:25.520 --> 00:49:28.150
Is that successful?

00:49:28.150 --> 00:49:34.110
So yeah, you can get a lot done
with adrenaline, and we do.

00:49:34.110 --> 00:49:37.090
But does it give you a relaxing,
content, fulfilled life?

00:49:37.090 --> 00:49:38.422
That's the question.

00:49:38.422 --> 00:49:39.130
AUDIENCE: Got it.

00:49:39.130 --> 00:49:39.630
Thank you.

00:49:42.520 --> 00:49:44.040
AUDIENCE: Hi, thanks, Doctor.

00:49:44.040 --> 00:49:46.290
I wanted to know-- so if,
let's say, a person has

00:49:46.290 --> 00:49:48.600
chronic pain, how to
they diagnose whether it

00:49:48.600 --> 00:49:51.180
is structurally or mentally.

00:49:51.180 --> 00:49:53.669
DAVID HANSCOM: So
again, this holds

00:49:53.669 --> 00:49:55.710
for all pain, migraine
headaches, whatever it is.

00:49:55.710 --> 00:49:58.680
So since I've taken
the pain project,

00:49:58.680 --> 00:50:00.420
I'm hyper about
doing the work-up.

00:50:00.420 --> 00:50:02.919
In other words, I'll make sure
it's not a tumor or infection

00:50:02.919 --> 00:50:04.450
or something
causing the problem.

00:50:04.450 --> 00:50:05.640
But what I'm seeing
with these patients

00:50:05.640 --> 00:50:08.160
with surgical problems, those
weren't structural problems.

00:50:08.160 --> 00:50:10.110
And historically, I would have
done surgery in a heartbeat,

00:50:10.110 --> 00:50:11.730
even by my
conservative standards.

00:50:11.730 --> 00:50:13.390
And they would have
done pretty well,

00:50:13.390 --> 00:50:14.820
but some of them wouldn't.

00:50:14.820 --> 00:50:17.070
So what happens-- I tease
my fellows about this--

00:50:17.070 --> 00:50:18.945
when was last time you
saw a surgical failure

00:50:18.945 --> 00:50:19.770
in my practice?

00:50:19.770 --> 00:50:20.910
And they don't.

00:50:20.910 --> 00:50:23.160
For elective surgery, we go
through this rehab process

00:50:23.160 --> 00:50:24.420
before surgery.

00:50:24.420 --> 00:50:26.770
Patients' outcomes
are spectacular.

00:50:26.770 --> 00:50:29.250
We have this whole group of
patients, even with bone spurs,

00:50:29.250 --> 00:50:31.140
that are cancelling the surgery
because their pain disappeared.

00:50:31.140 --> 00:50:33.181
It wasn't because they
were living with the pain.

00:50:33.181 --> 00:50:34.480
The pain actually disappeared.

00:50:34.480 --> 00:50:35.490
So I'm actually shocked.

00:50:35.490 --> 00:50:36.331
I had no idea.

00:50:36.331 --> 00:50:38.580
Every time that happens,
which happens every week now,

00:50:38.580 --> 00:50:39.460
I just shake my head.

00:50:39.460 --> 00:50:40.920
I'm going, what's going on?

00:50:40.920 --> 00:50:42.465
So it's been very interesting.

00:50:46.780 --> 00:50:48.860
AUDIENCE: Thank you for
coming to talk with us.

00:50:48.860 --> 00:50:50.780
I noticed that throughout
your presentation,

00:50:50.780 --> 00:50:52.250
at no point in
time you mentioned

00:50:52.250 --> 00:50:54.500
the idea of physical
therapy or any form

00:50:54.500 --> 00:50:55.790
of chiropractic intervention.

00:50:55.790 --> 00:50:56.480
DAVID HANSCOM: Right.

00:50:56.480 --> 00:50:58.640
AUDIENCE: I'm a big supporter
of Dr. Stuart McGill,

00:50:58.640 --> 00:50:59.510
and I've read most of his--

00:50:59.510 --> 00:51:00.020
DAVID HANSCOM: Who?

00:51:00.020 --> 00:51:00.950
AUDIENCE: Dr. Stuart McGill.

00:51:00.950 --> 00:51:01.400
DAVID HANSCOM: Yeah.

00:51:01.400 --> 00:51:02.810
AUDIENCE: Yeah, and so I've
read most of his major works,

00:51:02.810 --> 00:51:05.350
and he's very much so on
supporting and stabilizing

00:51:05.350 --> 00:51:06.020
the spine--

00:51:06.020 --> 00:51:06.440
DAVID HANSCOM: Right.

00:51:06.440 --> 00:51:07.760
AUDIENCE: --and just
getting comfortable

00:51:07.760 --> 00:51:09.926
in certain positions, and
then expanding from there.

00:51:09.926 --> 00:51:11.900
I was curious on your
thoughts on his work,

00:51:11.900 --> 00:51:15.520
and why you haven't been a
proponent of physical therapy.

00:51:15.520 --> 00:51:16.520
DAVID HANSCOM: Oh, I am.

00:51:16.520 --> 00:51:18.350
So I've picked up the
forest fire section.

00:51:18.350 --> 00:51:20.309
Normally, when I give
this talk-- my goal today

00:51:20.309 --> 00:51:22.808
is to create this paradigm shift
that you can heal yourself.

00:51:22.808 --> 00:51:23.930
I hope that came through.

00:51:23.930 --> 00:51:25.790
So it turns out that you have
to address all your variables

00:51:25.790 --> 00:51:28.060
at once with sleep, stress,
medication management,

00:51:28.060 --> 00:51:30.117
but physical condition is huge.

00:51:30.117 --> 00:51:31.700
So I'm a proponent
of the weight room.

00:51:31.700 --> 00:51:34.580
I like acupuncture,
chiropractic, physical therapy.

00:51:34.580 --> 00:51:36.830
It's been a wonderful thing
for my physical therapists

00:51:36.830 --> 00:51:39.590
because they do their thing,
but the book and the process

00:51:39.590 --> 00:51:41.880
takes care of the sleep,
the stress, whatever it is.

00:51:41.880 --> 00:51:44.360
So no, physical therapy is
a huge part of the deal.

00:51:44.360 --> 00:51:47.420
Remember, everything works
in chronic pain a little bit,

00:51:47.420 --> 00:51:49.430
but nothing works by itself.

00:51:49.430 --> 00:51:51.580
So sleep could be 25%-30%.

00:51:51.580 --> 00:51:53.711
Stress management
could be another 30%.

00:51:53.711 --> 00:51:55.460
Physical therapy could
be another 20%-25%.

00:51:55.460 --> 00:51:58.457
So when you start adding
these things together,

00:51:58.457 --> 00:51:59.540
it makes a big difference.

00:51:59.540 --> 00:52:01.090
So you're in good
physical shape.

00:52:01.090 --> 00:52:02.470
So physical therapy,
probably for you,

00:52:02.470 --> 00:52:04.180
is not as important as
some of these other things

00:52:04.180 --> 00:52:05.960
that people who are
grossly out of shape.

00:52:05.960 --> 00:52:08.800
So everybody has different,
I use the word "formula,"

00:52:08.800 --> 00:52:10.750
because everybody is different.

00:52:10.750 --> 00:52:12.470
So by definition,
if you're unique,

00:52:12.470 --> 00:52:15.350
and I'm unique, which we
are, then the only person

00:52:15.350 --> 00:52:17.950
who can solve my problem
is going to be me.

00:52:17.950 --> 00:52:19.284
I can't get inside your brain.

00:52:19.284 --> 00:52:20.700
So yeah, the
physical conditioning

00:52:20.700 --> 00:52:22.510
is a huge, huge
factor in this thing.

00:52:22.510 --> 00:52:23.790
And that's all in the book.

00:52:23.790 --> 00:52:24.650
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:52:24.650 --> 00:52:25.483
DAVID HANSCOM: Yeah.

00:52:27.500 --> 00:52:29.370
AUDIENCE: Thanks so
much for your talk.

00:52:29.370 --> 00:52:33.280
I can confirm that taking
stress out of your life

00:52:33.280 --> 00:52:34.480
gets rid of chronic pain.

00:52:34.480 --> 00:52:36.270
I had lower back pain for years.

00:52:36.270 --> 00:52:39.580
And once I started taking
out a bit stress of my life

00:52:39.580 --> 00:52:43.960
and don't take work as
seriously, to a certain extent,

00:52:43.960 --> 00:52:44.680
really helped me.

00:52:44.680 --> 00:52:45.544
DAVID HANSCOM: Good.

00:52:45.544 --> 00:52:46.960
AUDIENCE: I have
a question around

00:52:46.960 --> 00:52:50.394
adrenalin because it's like--

00:52:50.394 --> 00:52:53.230
the talk about adrenaline
slightly confused me

00:52:53.230 --> 00:52:56.880
because what is the right
level of adrenaline?

00:52:56.880 --> 00:52:59.590
Or maybe, what's the
difference between adrenaline

00:52:59.590 --> 00:53:00.850
and dopamine?

00:53:00.850 --> 00:53:04.040
Because for example,
if I do a sport,

00:53:04.040 --> 00:53:06.790
I get an adrenaline rush, but
the outcome is successful.

00:53:06.790 --> 00:53:09.069
I mean, I have a dopamine rush.

00:53:09.069 --> 00:53:10.360
Like, what's the right balance?

00:53:10.360 --> 00:53:13.120
Because now I'm a bit
afraid to expose myself

00:53:13.120 --> 00:53:15.760
to too much adrenaline,
and so I don't

00:53:15.760 --> 00:53:17.020
know what the right level is.

00:53:17.020 --> 00:53:19.630
DAVID HANSCOM: So I wish
I had more time here.

00:53:19.630 --> 00:53:22.030
My wife and I do workshops
together over a three or four

00:53:22.030 --> 00:53:22.550
day period of time.

00:53:22.550 --> 00:53:24.466
By the way, we're doing
a workshop in New York

00:53:24.466 --> 00:53:27.040
this June 29 through July
1, a three-day workshop.

00:53:27.040 --> 00:53:28.844
It'll be on my
website here shortly.

00:53:28.844 --> 00:53:30.760
The reality is we don't
really know the answer

00:53:30.760 --> 00:53:31.970
to that question.

00:53:31.970 --> 00:53:33.820
And so the goal
here isn't trying

00:53:33.820 --> 00:53:35.110
to control things around you.

00:53:35.110 --> 00:53:36.735
In other words, I
put that ring of fire

00:53:36.735 --> 00:53:38.290
out there because
what happens, you

00:53:38.290 --> 00:53:40.270
become comfortable going back
and forth through the rings.

00:53:40.270 --> 00:53:42.210
So the amount of
adrenaline doesn't matter.

00:53:42.210 --> 00:53:44.830
So I probably have five
times the stress on my plate

00:53:44.830 --> 00:53:48.050
right now than I had when
I broke 20 years ago.

00:53:48.050 --> 00:53:49.960
So what happens is you
just train your brain

00:53:49.960 --> 00:53:51.415
not to be adrenalized
when you deal with stress.

00:53:51.415 --> 00:53:53.110
Because remember,
stress, by definition,

00:53:53.110 --> 00:53:56.020
is a threat, which
is always adrenaline.

00:53:56.020 --> 00:53:58.696
Otherwise, it wouldn't
be stress, right?

00:53:58.696 --> 00:54:00.070
So what you do is
a lot of things

00:54:00.070 --> 00:54:01.360
that we perceive as stress--

00:54:01.360 --> 00:54:03.400
stress, which our
thoughts are, a lot of it

00:54:03.400 --> 00:54:04.620
is perceived stress--

00:54:04.620 --> 00:54:07.470
you start training your brain
just to have less adrenaline.

00:54:07.470 --> 00:54:10.420
And so you quit avoiding stress.

00:54:10.420 --> 00:54:12.540
You really can just
process almost anything.

00:54:12.540 --> 00:54:13.390
And I fail.

00:54:13.390 --> 00:54:15.760
We have some pretty
bad weeks and stuff.

00:54:15.760 --> 00:54:18.370
So I always tell my patients,
learn how to fail well,

00:54:18.370 --> 00:54:19.912
because these pathways
are permanent.

00:54:19.912 --> 00:54:21.494
You're always going
to be adrenalized.

00:54:21.494 --> 00:54:23.080
You always kick
these things back up.

00:54:23.080 --> 00:54:25.900
But you just process them more
quickly and more efficiently.

00:54:25.900 --> 00:54:27.690
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:54:27.690 --> 00:54:31.130
DAVID HANSCOM: I guess
one last question?

00:54:31.130 --> 00:54:33.290
AUDIENCE: Going back
to the physical side,

00:54:33.290 --> 00:54:35.780
if you are working on
your back, whether it

00:54:35.780 --> 00:54:38.180
be massage or physical
activity, anything

00:54:38.180 --> 00:54:39.770
in particular that
you do recommend,

00:54:39.770 --> 00:54:42.080
either massage-wise
or specific exercises

00:54:42.080 --> 00:54:43.440
to strengthen the back?

00:54:43.440 --> 00:54:44.460
DAVID HANSCOM: Yeah,
I like them both.

00:54:44.460 --> 00:54:45.860
I mean, I think that
things like massage,

00:54:45.860 --> 00:54:47.590
for instance, gives you a
different set of sensations.

00:54:47.590 --> 00:54:50.420
So I think there's, first of
all, a relaxation effect which

00:54:50.420 --> 00:54:51.770
decreases the adrenaline.

00:54:51.770 --> 00:54:54.230
But you're also substituting
the neurological impulses

00:54:54.230 --> 00:54:56.480
on the part of the
body that's painful.

00:54:56.480 --> 00:54:57.680
I love the weight room.

00:54:57.680 --> 00:54:59.800
Obviously strengthening
and conditioning helps.

00:54:59.800 --> 00:55:02.660
